# Food Truck Activation Kit C: Founder Ops and Attribution Ledger

**Bishop SEG-KIT-C | Authored: 2026-06-10 | Status: READY-FOR-RATIFY**
**Applies to: BP079 floor mode while Knight Wave A+B ship**
**Statute bindings: §3 Sonnet 4.6, §5 83.3% doctrine, BP078 three-currency-no-fiat, Truth-Always**

---

## Purpose

Founder needs operational infrastructure that works TODAY, before Knight ships the `promotion_attributions` table (Wave A) and the in-app Cue Card generator (Wave B). This kit gives Founder:

- A working Stripe payment link he can hand a food-truck owner on the sidewalk
- A manual attribution ledger so introducer credit is captured the moment the conversation happens
- Protocols for Bishop to maintain that ledger across sessions
- A backfill SEG to run the day Wave A goes green

Once Wave A+B land, this kit becomes the import source for the first N attributions. It does not become obsolete; it becomes the audit trail.

---

## §1. Stripe Dashboard Setup (Floor-Mode Checkout Link)

### What you are building

Two Stripe products and one Payment Link. The $5/year membership is what the food-truck owner pays to join Liana Banyan as a member. The weekly meal-prep subscription is a separate product the food-truck owner sells to LB members who subscribe to that merchant's service. These are two distinct flows on two distinct payment surfaces. Do not conflate them.

**$5/year product = the food-truck owner paying LB to join**
**Weekly meal-prep product = LB members paying the food-truck owner for food**

The floor-mode Payment Link you hand the food-truck owner covers the $5/year membership only. The meal-prep subscription product is a separate Stripe product you configure in advance so that once the owner is a member, Knight Wave B can wire their merchant node and issue them a Cue Card pointing subscribers to THAT product.

---

### Step 1. $5/Year Membership Product

Navigate in Stripe dashboard: **Products** (left sidebar) > **+ Add product**

Fill in:

- **Name:** `Liana Banyan Annual Membership`
- **Description:** `Annual membership for Workers, Builders, and Creators on the Liana Banyan platform. Includes full platform access, local AI memory, and cooperative attribution rights.`
- **Statement descriptor:** `LIANA BANYAN MEMBERSHIP` (Stripe allows up to 22 characters; Founder confirms exact truncation behavior in dashboard under Account Settings > Business Settings > Statement descriptor)
- **Pricing model:** Recurring
- **Billing period:** Yearly
- **Price:** $5.00 USD
- **Tax behavior:** Select "Exclusive" (tax is added on top of $5.00). Then enable Stripe Tax (Products > Tax settings) and set the product's tax code to `txcd_10000000` (general digital services) or Founder confirms with accountant. Auto-tax handles multi-state obligations automatically at this price point.

**Metadata to add on the product record** (Products > [product name] > Metadata section):

```
platform: liana_banyan
member_class: general
attribution_eligible: true
currency_class_on_signup: Credits
```

Note: these metadata fields live on the product record, not on individual checkout sessions. Session-level metadata (who the introducer is) is set on the Payment Link in Step 3.

If this product already exists in your Stripe account, skip this step and locate it under Products. Note its Product ID (starts with `prod_`) for reference.

---

### Step 2. Weekly Meal-Prep Subscription Product

This product is a template you configure once per merchant. You will create a new copy (or a new Price on the same Product) for each food-truck owner who joins.

Navigate: **Products** > **+ Add product**

- **Name template:** `Weekly Meal Prep: [Business Name]` (example: `Weekly Meal Prep: Joe's Rolling Kitchen`)
- **Description:** `Weekly meal-prep subscription through the Liana Banyan cooperative network. Workers, Builders, and Creators keep 83.3% of every transaction.`
- **Pricing model:** Recurring
- **Billing period:** Weekly
- **Price:** Founder sets based on local market. Suggested starting range for a food-truck operator: $25 to $65/week depending on portion count and region. Do not hardcode a default here; the merchant sets their price and Founder enters it.
- **Tax behavior:** Exclusive (same rationale as membership product)

**Metadata on the product record:**

```
platform: liana_banyan
node_type: food
merchant_type: food_truck
business_entity_id: [fill at onboarding, leave blank until merchant has auth.users.id]
introducer_user_id: [Founder's auth.users.id from Supabase; get this before floor mode opens]
```

**How to find Founder's auth.users.id:** Knight has access to the Supabase `auth.users` table. Before going to floor mode, ask Knight for a read on `SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = '<founder_email>'` and record it. Alternatively, Founder can find it in the Supabase dashboard: Authentication > Users > locate your account > copy the UUID in the ID column.

Record this UUID somewhere permanent (your MEMORY.md or a pinned note). Every product and payment link you create needs it in metadata.

---

### Step 3. Stripe Payment Link Generation

This is the link you hand the food-truck owner. It handles the $5/year membership signup.

Navigate: **Payment Links** (left sidebar) > **+ New**

1. **Product selection:** Add the `Liana Banyan Annual Membership` product. Confirm price is $5.00 / year.
2. **Quantity:** Set to 1, locked (no adjustment by customer).
3. **Collect customer information:** Enable email collection. This is how you match the Stripe customer to an LB member account later.
4. **Metadata on this Payment Link:** Stripe allows metadata at the Payment Link level that propagates to every Checkout Session created from the link. Click "Additional options" or "Metadata" depending on your Stripe dashboard version (Founder confirms exact UI label). Add:

```
introducer_user_id: [Founder's UUID from Step 2]
business_name_target: [e.g., "Joe's Rolling Kitchen"]
merchant_type: food_truck
cue_card_token: floor_mode_[ISO-8601 datetime with colons replaced by hyphens, e.g., floor_mode_2026-06-10T18-45-00Z]
kit_version: kit_c_bp079
```

**Note on introducer_user_id:** Get this UUID from Knight before creating your first Payment Link. A Yoke is in flight to retrieve it. See `BISHOP_YOKE_FOUNDER_UUID_2026-06-10.md` in the BISHOP_DROPZONE for the result. Do not proceed to Step 5 without this value populated.

**Metadata limit note (binding Truth-Always constraint):** Stripe enforces a maximum of 50 metadata keys and 500 characters per value on Payment Links and Checkout Sessions. The fields above are well within the key limit. The value for `cue_card_token` plus `introducer_user_id` plus `business_name_target` will not approach 500 characters unless the business name is extremely long. If a future iteration of this kit adds a cue card payload (JSON, encoded content, etc.) to the metadata value, that value WILL hit the 500-character limit and the floor mode will break silently at checkout. At that point, Founder must switch to creating Checkout Sessions via the Stripe API (not the dashboard Payment Link UI) to carry a full payload. This is a known forward constraint; it does not affect the $5 membership floor mode described here.

5. **Usage limit:** If Founder wants this link to be specific to one food-truck owner (single-shot), set "Limit to 1 use" under Advanced options. If Founder wants a reusable link to hand to any food-truck owner (generic introducer attribution), set no limit. The trade-off: a single-shot link gives clean attribution (you know exactly who used it); a no-limit link is simpler to hand out but requires the `business_name_target` metadata to match the correct merchant. Recommended for floor mode: create one Payment Link per merchant conversation. It takes 30 seconds and the attribution is unambiguous.

6. **After-payment redirect:** Under "Confirmation page," select "Redirect to URL" and enter a landing page you control. Until Knight Wave B ships the `CueCardLanding` component, use a static URL such as your current download page (`https://mnemosynec.ai/download` or equivalent) with a query parameter appended for tracking: `?source=floor_mode&kit=c`. The redirect does not need to be functional for attribution to work; attribution is captured at checkout session creation, not at redirect load.

7. **Save and copy the link.** The link format will be `https://buy.stripe.com/[random_id]`. Copy this URL. You will paste it into the attribution ledger in §2 and hand it to the food-truck owner verbally, via text message, or on a physical card.

---

### Step 4. Tax and Reporting Setup

**Sales tax (for the $5/year membership):** Stripe Tax with "Exclusive" pricing handles this automatically if enabled. The $5 amount is the platform fee; tax is added on top. Founder does not need to configure per-state rates manually. Navigate: Settings > Tax > Enable Stripe Tax, connect your business address, and select automatic tax calculation. Stripe Tax costs 0.5% of transactions in jurisdictions where it calculates tax. On a $5 transaction this is $0.025, negligible.

**Sales tax (for the weekly meal-prep subscription):** The food-truck merchant is the seller of the food subscription, not LB. LB is the platform. LB collects a platform fee (Cost+20% on the merchant's subscription revenue, once Wave B wires this) but does not collect or remit sales tax on food sales. The merchant bears that obligation. LB's platform fee is a B2B service fee, not a retail food sale. Founder should confirm this characterization with an accountant before going beyond floor mode at scale. At the pilot stage (one merchant, one link), the tax exposure is minimal.

**1099 / W-9 for the food-truck merchant:** The food-truck owner, once operating as a merchant node on the platform, is a vendor receiving payments through LB's platform infrastructure. If annual payments to that merchant through LB exceed $600 in a calendar year, LB has a potential 1099-NEC or 1099-K reporting obligation depending on how the payment flow is structured. At the pilot stage and $5/year membership, there is no 1099 obligation on the membership payment itself. The 1099 question becomes live when recurring meal-prep subscription revenue routes through LB and LB remits the merchant's share. Founder should have a W-9 on file for each merchant before that revenue flow begins. Until Wave B is live and routing merchant payments, this is a forward-planning item, not a today item.

**Bookkeeping label convention:** In Stripe, every Payment Link can be tagged with a label visible in your dashboard exports. Use this naming convention in the "Internal note" or "Description" field on the Payment Link:

`LB_FLOOR_MODE | FOOD_TRUCK | [Business Name] | BP079 | [YYYY-MM-DD]`

This makes the transaction identifiable in Stripe CSV exports, in your accounting system, and in the attribution ledger without ambiguity.

---

### Step 5. Test Link Verification

Before going to floor mode with a live link, verify in Stripe test mode.

1. Toggle Stripe to **Test mode** (top-right toggle in Stripe dashboard, labeled "Test mode").
2. Create a second Payment Link using the same steps above, but in test mode. The link will start with `https://buy.stripe.com/test_...`.
3. Open the test link in a browser (incognito window recommended).
4. Complete a test checkout using Stripe's test card: `4242 4242 4242 4242`, any future expiry, any CVC, any ZIP.
5. After payment, confirm in Stripe dashboard (still in test mode): **Events** (left sidebar) > find the most recent `checkout.session.completed` event. Click into it and verify:
   - `metadata.introducer_user_id` is present and matches what you entered
   - `metadata.merchant_type` is `food_truck`
   - `metadata.cue_card_token` is present
   - `customer_email` is captured
6. Verify the after-payment redirect lands on your target URL (browser tab should show the redirect destination).
7. Switch back to **Live mode** before using the link with a real food-truck owner. The test-mode link does NOT accept real cards.

If any metadata field is missing in the test event, return to the Payment Link, edit the metadata, and re-test. Do not go live until metadata is confirmed present in the `checkout.session.completed` event object.

