## §6. Truth-Always Footnotes

**1. Stripe metadata limits will break floor mode if cue card payload exceeds 500 characters per value.**

Floor-mode rule (Founder ratified 2026-06-10): Founder keeps metadata to the five baseline fields in §1 Step 3. Richer payload (cue card JSON, benefit text, referral codes, deep links) waits for Wave B API-created Checkout Sessions.

Stripe enforces a 500-character maximum per metadata value and a 50-key maximum per object. The five baseline fields fit comfortably. If a future version of this kit embeds a full cue card JSON payload inside a single metadata value, that value WILL exceed 500 characters. The Payment Link will still process the checkout, but the oversized metadata value will be silently truncated or rejected depending on Stripe's behavior at that time. The fix is to create Checkout Sessions via the Stripe API (not the dashboard Payment Link UI) and pass full metadata programmatically. This is Knight Wave B territory. For floor mode with the five metadata fields listed, you are safe.

**2. The $5/year membership and the weekly meal-prep subscription are two completely separate payment flows.**

The food-truck owner pays $5/year to become an LB member. That is one Stripe checkout, one product, one payment.

LB members who want weekly meal-prep from that food-truck owner pay a separate weekly subscription to that merchant. That is a different Stripe product, a different payment, and a different checkout flow that does not exist in floor mode yet. Wave B builds the in-app checkout surface for the meal-prep subscription. Do not tell a food-truck owner they are signing up for both today. Today they are signing up for membership only.

The platform fee (Cost+20%) applies to the merchant subscription revenue stream, not to the $5/year membership. LB does not take 20% of the $5 membership fee in the sense of extracting a cut; the $5 is the platform membership price directly. The Cost+20% doctrine applies to the goods-and-services transactions that route through the platform once Wave B is live.

**3. Introducer credit is not fiat-convertible. Ever.**

Founder recording an attribution in this ledger does not create a USD receivable. The `introducer_credit_class` field records Credits, Marks, or Joules per the BP078 three-currency canon. These accrue in the ledger and in `promotion_attributions` once backfilled. They are redeemable through the platform's substitution economy. They are not exchangeable for dollars. Cash income to Founder from this activity happens through actual hiring and payment cycles (a merchant hires Founder for a service, a member pays Founder for work done) not through currency conversion. If Founder reads this kit and expects a USD payout when the food-truck owner pays $5, that expectation does not match the canon. The $5 goes to LB platform revenue. Founder's credit is attributed in the ledger and vests per the canonical vesting window (TBD by Knight Wave B). Substitution makes prior work more valuable over time; it does not create a conversion event.

**4. Sales tax and 1099 obligations belong to the merchant, not to LB, for the food services flow.**

LB is a platform intermediary. The food-truck merchant sells food subscriptions. LB collects a platform fee on that revenue. The merchant is responsible for food sales tax in their jurisdiction. LB is responsible for reporting its own platform fee income. Whether LB has a 1099 obligation to the merchant depends on total annual payment volume and payment routing structure. At pilot scale, Founder should get a W-9 on file before routing any meal-prep subscription revenue through LB accounts. Nothing in this kit constitutes tax advice. Confirm with an accountant before going past the pilot.

**W-9 collection note:** W-9 collection from food-truck merchants is added to the Wave B onboarding spec per Founder ratification 2026-06-10. In floor mode, Founder collects W-9 manually before any meal-prep subscription revenue routes through LB. Wave B will wire this into the merchant onboarding flow automatically.

**5. Floor mode is temporary and will not scale manually.**

The protocols in this kit are designed for Founder's first few dozen conversations. They will become unwieldy at 100 rows and unmanageable at 1,000. Wave A+B replace the manual ledger with automated attribution at checkout. The manual ledger's purpose is to capture attribution that would otherwise be lost during the gap between today's floor-mode conversations and Knight's delivery. Once Wave A is live and the backfill SEG has run, the ledger is an audit trail, not an active workflow. Founder should not build processes that depend on the ledger being the long-term system of record.

